  <subfield code="o">2</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">Different search keywords will get different datasets, here, we use the University of Western Australia as the search keywords. The citation network data uncovered a small number of papers with a very large number of authors. While the inclusion of these papers did not change our qualitative results, it did slow down our computational work and significantly skewed the degree distribution. To overcome this we only include manuscripts with fewer than 30 authors and report the results for analysis of that data in this paper</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">3</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">As described in a previous study [, 18: #epl18390bib18], choosing a small number of pairs of nodes (links) to compare is a benefit to observe the fluctuation of precision with the varying of α. Here, to distinguish the accuracies of different algorithms and observe their fluctuation, we choose the top 5% (or top m) pair of nodes to test</subfield>
